p.seg: JULY, 1919 QUARTERLY BULLETIN OF THE Nebraska State Department of Health LINCOLN, NEBRASKA VITAL STATISTICS NUMBER Birth and Death Reports for 1918

It is not to be understood that birth and death registration in Nebraska is by any means complete, as we are not accepted l>y the United States Census Bureau as a registration state for cither. The deaths are recorded under fourteen groups, viz. : 1. General diseases. '1. Nervous system and organs of special sense. 'A. Circulatory system. 4. Respiratory system. 5. Digestive system. (i. Non-venereal diseases of genito-urinary system and annexa. 7. Puerperal state. 8. Skin and cellular tissue. !). Bones and organs of locomotion 10. Malformations. 11. Early infancy. 12. Old age. 13. External causes. 14. Ill-defined. In the event that a county does not show more than a few groups under which diseases are classified, it indicates that no •liseases of the other groups were reported from that county. In other words, just those diseases reported are given under the specific groups. It is hoped that birth and death registration during the coming year will be given more attention than in the past, so that our statistics will be of more value.
